            {
              "id": "CVE-2025-59529",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "avahi: simple clients denial-of-service"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Avahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In versions up to and including 0.9-rc2, the simple protocol server ignores the documented client limit and accepts unlimited connections, allowing for easy local DoS. Although `CLIENTS_MAX` is defined, `server_work()` unconditionally `accept()`s and `client_new()` always appends the new client and increments `n_clients`. There is no check against the limit. When client cannot be accepted as a result of maximal socket number of avahi-daemon, it logs unconditionally error per each connection. Unprivileged local users can exhaust daemon memory and file descriptors, causing a denial of service system-wide for mDNS/DNS-SD. Exhausting local file descriptors causes increased system load caused by logging errors of each of request. Overloading prevents glibc calls using nss-mdns plugins to resolve `*.local.` names and link-local addresses. As of time of publication, no known patched versions are available, but a candidate fix is available in pull request 808, and some workarounds are available. Simple clients are offered for nss-mdns package functionality. It is not possible to disable the unix socket `/run/avahi-daemon/socket`, but resolution requests received via DBus are not affected directly. Tools avahi-resolve, avahi-resolve-address and avahi-resolve-host-name are not affected, they use DBus interface. It is possible to change permissions of unix socket after avahi-daemon is started. But avahi-daemon does not provide any configuration for it. Additional access restrictions like SELinux can also prevent unwanted tools to access the socket and keep resolution working for trusted users."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-59529",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-59529\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nPackage: avahi-libs\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2025-59529](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-59529)\nAvahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In versions up to and including 0.9-rc2, the simple protocol server ignores the documented client limit and accepts unlimited connections, allowing for easy local DoS. Although `CLIENTS_MAX` is defined, `server_work()` unconditionally `accept()`s and `client_new()` always appends the new client and increments `n_clients`. There is no check against the limit. When client cannot be accepted as a result of maximal socket number of avahi-daemon, it logs unconditionally error per each connection. Unprivileged local users can exhaust daemon memory and file descriptors, causing a denial of service system-wide for mDNS/DNS-SD. Exhausting local file descriptors causes increased system load caused by logging errors of each of request. Overloading prevents glibc calls using nss-mdns plugins to resolve `*.local.` names and link-local addresses. As of time of publication, no known patched versions are available, but a candidate fix is available in pull request 808, and some workarounds are available. Simple clients are offered for nss-mdns package functionality. It is not possible to disable the unix socket `/run/avahi-daemon/socket`, but resolution requests received via DBus are not affected directly. Tools avahi-resolve, avahi-resolve-address and avahi-resolve-host-name are not affected, they use DBus interface. It is possible to change permissions of unix socket after avahi-daemon is started. But avahi-daemon does not provide any configuration for it. Additional access restrictions like SELinux can also prevent unwanted tools to access the socket and keep resolution working for trusted users.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-59529**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|MEDIUM|avahi-libs||[CVE-2025-59529](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-59529)|\n\nAvahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In versions up to and including 0.9-rc2, the simple protocol server ignores the documented client limit and accepts unlimited connections, allowing for easy local DoS. Although `CLIENTS_MAX` is defined, `server_work()` unconditionally `accept()`s and `client_new()` always appends the new client and increments `n_clients`. There is no check against the limit. When client cannot be accepted as a result of maximal socket number of avahi-daemon, it logs unconditionally error per each connection. Unprivileged local users can exhaust daemon memory and file descriptors, causing a denial of service system-wide for mDNS/DNS-SD. Exhausting local file descriptors causes increased system load caused by logging errors of each of request. Overloading prevents glibc calls using nss-mdns plugins to resolve `*.local.` names and link-local addresses. As of time of publication, no known patched versions are available, but a candidate fix is available in pull request 808, and some workarounds are available. Simple clients are offered for nss-mdns package functionality. It is not possible to disable the unix socket `/run/avahi-daemon/socket`, but resolution requests received via DBus are not affected directly. Tools avahi-resolve, avahi-resolve-address and avahi-resolve-host-name are not affected, they use DBus interface. It is possible to change permissions of unix socket after avahi-daemon is started. But avahi-daemon does not provide any configuration for it. Additional access restrictions like SELinux can also prevent unwanted tools to access the socket and keep resolution working for trusted users."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv3_baseScore": 5.5,
                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:L/AC:L/PR:L/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H",
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "5.5",
                "tags": [
                  "vulnerability",
                  "security",
                  "MEDIUM"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "CVE-2025-68276",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "avahi: Avahi: Denial of Service via D-Bus record browsers with AVAHI_LOOKUP_USE_WIDE_AREA flag"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Avahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In 0.9-rc2 and earlier, an unprivileged local users can crash avahi-daemon (with wide-area disabled) by creating record browsers with the AVAHI_LOOKUP_USE_WIDE_AREA flag set via D-Bus. This can be done by either calling\nthe RecordBrowserNew method directly or creating hostname/address/service resolvers/browsers that create those browsers internally themselves."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-68276",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-68276\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nPackage: avahi-libs\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2025-68276](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-68276)\nAvahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In 0.9-rc2 and earlier, an unprivileged local users can crash avahi-daemon (with wide-area disabled) by creating record browsers with the AVAHI_LOOKUP_USE_WIDE_AREA flag set via D-Bus. This can be done by either calling\nthe RecordBrowserNew method directly or creating hostname/address/service resolvers/browsers that create those browsers internally themselves.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-68276**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|MEDIUM|avahi-libs||[CVE-2025-68276](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-68276)|\n\nAvahi is a system which facilitates service discovery on a local network via the mDNS/DNS-SD protocol suite. In 0.9-rc2 and earlier, an unprivileged local users can crash avahi-daemon (with wide-area disabled) by creating record browsers with the AVAHI_LOOKUP_USE_WIDE_AREA flag set via D-Bus. This can be done by either calling\nthe RecordBrowserNew method directly or creating hostname/address/service resolvers/browsers that create those browsers internally themselves."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cvssv3_baseScore": 5.5,
                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:L/AC:L/PR:N/UI:R/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H",
                "precision": "very-high",
                "security-severity": "5.5",
                "tags": [
