            {
              "id": "CVE-2026-4878",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "libcap: libcap: Privilege escalation via TOCTOU race condition in cap_set_file()"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "A flaw was found in libcap. A local unprivileged user can exploit a Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition in the `cap_set_file()` function. This allows an attacker with write access to a parent directory to redirect file capability updates to an attacker-controlled file. By doing so, capabilities can be injected into or stripped from unintended executables, leading to privilege escalation."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "error"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-4878",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-4878\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: libcap\nFixed Version: 2.48-6.el8_10.1\nLink: [CVE-2026-4878](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-4878)\nA flaw was found in libcap. A local unprivileged user can exploit a Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition in the `cap_set_file()` function. This allows an attacker with write access to a parent directory to redirect file capability updates to an attacker-controlled file. By doing so, capabilities can be injected into or stripped from unintended executables, leading to privilege escalation.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-4878**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|libcap|2.48-6.el8_10.1|[CVE-2026-4878](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-4878)|\n\nA flaw was found in libcap. A local unprivileged user can exploit a Time-of-check-to-time-of-use (TOCTOU) race condition in the `cap_set_file()` function. This allows an attacker with write access to a parent directory to redirect file capability updates to an attacker-controlled file. By doing so, capabilities can be injected into or stripped from unintended executables, leading to privilege escalation."
              },
