            {
              "id": "CVE-2025-9714",
              "name": "OsPackageVulnerability",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "libxslt: libxml2: Inifinite recursion at exsltDynMapFunction function in libexslt/dynamic.c"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "Uncontrolled recursion in XPath evaluation in libxml2 up to and including version 2.9.14 allows a local attacker to cause a stack overflow via crafted expressions. XPath processing functions `xmlXPathRunEval`, `xmlXPathCtxtCompile`, and `xmlXPathEvalExpr` were resetting recursion depth to zero before making potentially recursive calls. When such functions were called recursively this could allow for uncontrolled recursion and lead to a stack overflow. These functions now preserve recursion depth across recursive calls, allowing recursion depth to be controlled."
              },
              "defaultConfiguration": {
                "level": "warning"
              },
              "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-9714",
              "help": {
                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-9714\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nPackage: libxml2\nFixed Version: 2.9.7-21.el8_10.4\nLink: [CVE-2025-9714](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-9714)\nUncontrolled recursion in XPath evaluation in libxml2 up to and including version 2.9.14 allows a local attacker to cause a stack overflow via crafted expressions. XPath processing functions `xmlXPathRunEval`, `xmlXPathCtxtCompile`, and `xmlXPathEvalExpr` were resetting recursion depth to zero before making potentially recursive calls. When such functions were called recursively this could allow for uncontrolled recursion and lead to a stack overflow. These functions now preserve recursion depth across recursive calls, allowing recursion depth to be controlled.",
                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-9714**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|MEDIUM|libxml2|2.9.7-21.el8_10.4|[CVE-2025-9714](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-9714)|\n\nUncontrolled recursion in XPath evaluation in libxml2 up to and including version 2.9.14 allows a local attacker to cause a stack overflow via crafted expressions. XPath processing functions `xmlXPathRunEval`, `xmlXPathCtxtCompile`, and `xmlXPathEvalExpr` were resetting recursion depth to zero before making potentially recursive calls. When such functions were called recursively this could allow for uncontrolled recursion and lead to a stack overflow. These functions now preserve recursion depth across recursive calls, allowing recursion depth to be controlled."
              },
